Adult worms were found in the host’s egg mass (ovigerous females with eggs in initial, intermediate and final stages of development). All immature worms were found encysted in a mucus sheath without ornamentation in the following sites: on the ventral side of the abdomen, on the setae that follow the border of the abdomen, on the central axis of pleopods (
Figure 5B
), and on the setae of pleopods of non-ovigerous adult female crabs; on the ventral side of the abdomen, on the central axis of pleopods, and on the setae of pleopods of ovigerous females; at the ventral side of the abdomen, on the central axis of pleopods, and on the setae of pleopods of post-ovigerous females. No immature worms were found on male crabs.
